  "instructions": {
    "L": [
      {
        "S": "Marinate the chicken 1 to 24 hours ahead. Whisk together 3/4 cup yogurt, 2 tablespoons lemon juice, 1 1/2 tablespoons minced garlic, 1 tablespoon minced ginger, 2 teaspoons cumin, 1 teaspoon garam masala, 1 teaspoon paprika, 1 teaspoon coriander, 1/2 teaspoon turmeric, 1/2 teaspoon cinnamon, 1/4 teaspoon cayenne, 1/2 teaspoon black pepper, 1 teaspoon salt, and 1 tablespoon vegetable oil in a large bowl. Add 1 1/2 pounds chicken thigh pieces and turn to coat thoroughly. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate for at least 1 hour, or ideally overnight (up to 24 hours) for the best flavor."
      },
      {
        "S": "Remove chicken from the fridge 15 minutes before cooking. Heat 1 tablespoon additional vegetable oil in a large non-stick or cast-iron skillet over high heat until the pan is very hot and nearly smoking. Working in 2 to 3 batches to avoid crowding, add chicken in a single layer. Cook undisturbed for 3 minutes until charred on the bottom, then flip and cook 2 to 3 minutes on the second side until charred. Transfer to a plate. Between batches, scrape out any burnt bits and add a little more oil if needed. The chicken does not need to be cooked through at this stage."
      },
      {
        "S": "Build the sauce by reducing heat to medium. In the same skillet (wipe clean if heavily charred), melt 2 tablespoons butter with 2 tablespoons vegetable oil. Add 1 finely diced large yellow onion and a pinch of salt. Cook, stirring frequently, until softened and lightly golden, about 5 to 7 minutes. Add 1 tablespoon minced ginger and cook 1 minute. Add 3 cloves minced garlic and cook 1 minute more until fragrant."
      },
      {
        "S": "Bloom the spices by adding 2 teaspoons ground cumin, 2 teaspoons paprika, 1 teaspoon ground coriander, 1 teaspoon turmeric, 1 tablespoon garam masala, and 1 teaspoon salt to the skillet. Stir constantly for 30 to 60 seconds until the spices are fragrant and coat the onions. This step is essential to develop deep flavor."
      },
      {
        "S": "Pour in 1 (14 ounce) can tomato sauce and 1/2 cup water. Stir well, scraping up any browned bits from the pan bottom. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low. Cover and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the sauce thickens and turns a deep, rich color."
      },
      {
        "S": "Blend the sauce for restaurant-quality smoothness (optional but recommended). Carefully transfer the sauce to a bowl and use an immersion blender or countertop blender to puree until smooth. Return sauce to the skillet. Skip this step if you prefer a chunkier, more rustic sauce."
      },
      {
        "S": "Stir 1 cup heavy cream or coconut milk and 1 teaspoon sugar into the sauce. Add the seared chicken along with any accumulated juices. Stir to coat. Simmer uncovered over medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes, or until the chicken is cooked through to an internal temperature of 165 degrees Fahrenheit and the sauce reaches your desired consistency. Add a splash of water if the sauce is too thick."
      },
      {
        "S": "Remove from heat. Stir in 2 tablespoons cold butter for extra richness and gloss if desired. Taste and adjust salt and spice levels. Stir in half of the 1/4 cup chopped cilantro."
      },
      {
        "S": "Spoon over 5 cups hot cooked basmati rice (about 1 cup per serving) or alongside warm naan bread. Garnish with remaining fresh cilantro and lemon wedges. Serve immediately."
      }
    ]
  },
  "notes": {
    "L": [
      {
        "S": "Chicken Thighs vs. Breasts: Thighs are strongly recommended. Their higher fat content keeps them juicy through high-heat charring and extended simmering. If using breasts, reduce the charring time and monitor closely to avoid dryness."
      },
      {
        "S": "Heat Level: This version uses 1/4 teaspoon cayenne for mild heat. Adjust up to 1 teaspoon for medium heat, or substitute with 1 teaspoon Kashmiri chili powder for vibrant color with gentle warmth."
      },
      {
        "S": "Dairy-Free Substitution: Replace yogurt with coconut yogurt for the marinade. Use coconut milk instead of heavy cream in the sauce. Replace butter with coconut oil or vegan butter."
      },
      {
        "S": "Gluten-Free: This recipe is naturally gluten-free as written. If serving with naan, use gluten-free naan."
      },
      {
        "S": "Make-Ahead and Storage: The cooked curry keeps refrigerated for up to 3 days or frozen for up to 3 months. Reheat gently on the stove with a splash of water. A pinch of garam masala when reheating refreshes the spice aromatics."
      },
      {
        "S": "Oil Choice: Use a neutral, high-smoke-point oil such as vegetable, canola, or grapeseed. Avoid olive oil for the charring step."
      },
      {
        "S": "Food Safety: Always ensure chicken reaches an internal temperature of 165 degrees Fahrenheit (74 degrees Celsius). When reheating leftovers, bring to a full simmer before serving."
      }
    ]
  },
